# Backend — Hex Architecture

## Layer layout

```
apps/backend/src/
  domain/          # Entities, value objects, domain errors. Zero framework/ORM imports.
  application/     # Use-cases (services). Depend on ports, not adapters.
  ports/           # Interfaces (e.g. FolderRepository). Application-owned contracts.
  adapters/
    db/            # Drizzle implementations of ports
    http/          # Elysia controllers, request/response schemas
  infrastructure/  # Bootstrap, DI wiring, config, logger
```

Dependency direction is strictly inward: `adapters → application → domain`. Domain never imports from adapters.

## SOLID in practice

- **SRP:** One use-case per file (`listChildren.ts`, `searchFolders.ts`). Controllers only translate HTTP ↔ use-case input/output.
- **DIP:** Services take port interfaces via constructor injection. No `new DrizzleFolderRepo()` inside services.
- **OCP:** Add a new storage or search backend by implementing a port, not by editing the service.

## REST conventions

- Base path: `/api/v1`. Resource-based URIs: `/folders`, `/folders/:id/children`, `/folders/search`.
- Verbs: `GET` read, `POST` create, `PUT`/`PATCH` update, `DELETE` remove.
- Status codes: `200`, `201`, `204`, `400`, `404`, `409`, `422`, `500`. No `200 { error }`.
- Validate every input with Elysia's schema (`t.Object`) — never trust params/body.
- Paginate list endpoints with cursor params (`?cursor=&limit=`); default and cap `limit`.

## Reliability & debuggability

- Throw typed domain errors (`FolderNotFoundError`); map to HTTP in one place (error handler middleware).
- Every request gets a `requestId` (header or generated); include it in every log line and error response.
- Use a structured logger (e.g. `pino`). No `console.log` in committed code outside `infrastructure/logger`.
- All config via env vars loaded/validated once at startup. Fail fast on missing config.

## Example — wiring a use-case

```ts
export class ListChildren {
  constructor(private readonly folders: FolderRepository) {}
  async exec(input: { parentId: string; cursor?: string; limit: number }) {
    return this.folders.listChildren(input);
  }
}
```

Controller calls `new ListChildren(repo).exec(parsed)` — no business logic in the controller.
